                  <strong><a href="/members/rapallo">rapallo</a></strong>
                  <span>on</span>
                  <a href="#comment-95022" name="comment-95022">October 28, 2005 at 10:26 am</a>
                  <p>A magnificent &ldquo;recreation&rdquo;, as opposed to &ldquo;restoration&rdquo;. Having been completely gutted in the early 1970&rsquo;s to create a shopping plaza (excuse the pun), the incredible recreation of this 1929 theatre must be seen to be believed. &ldquo;THE&rdquo; Cinema Recreation treasure of the 20th Century.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="comment odd">
                <div class="avatar"><a href="/members/donald4564"><img alt="donald4564" height="48" src="/images/avatars/small.png?1714499759" width="48" /></a></div>
                <div class="body">
                  <strong><a href="/members/donald4564">donald4564</a></strong>
                  <span>on</span>
                  <a href="#comment-139455" name="comment-139455">August 11, 2006 at  4:50 am</a>
                  <p>The Plaza opened in 1929 as a talkie only cinema and had a small 2 manual cinema organ. This organ ened up first in Darwin and is now in Adelaide. The original plans for the Plaza&rsquo;s use as a cabaret/ballroom seem not to have been altered too much as the sides of the auditorium were flanked by very large colonades.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
